          "body": "The placement of Psalm 120 as the first of the fifteen Songs of Ascents (Psalms 120–134) creates a canonical frame that no single-psalm reading can fully capture. The collection was sung by pilgrims ascending to Jerusalem for the three annual feasts, each step up the mountain road accompanied by one of these psalms. By beginning the collection in Meshech — the hostile outer edge of the world — the editors set up a journey whose destination is Zion's shalom. Each subsequent psalm moves the pilgrim closer: Psalm 121 introduces the God who keeps Israel in the journey; Psalm 122 names Jerusalem and the houses of David; Psalm 128 describes the peace of the household; Psalm 134 blesses from Zion itself. Psalm 120's unresolved ache is precisely what makes the journey necessary and the arrival meaningful. The theological implication for the Christian reader is profound: the New Testament identifies Jesus as the one who 'came and preached peace to you who were far away and peace to those who were near' (Ephesians 2:17), citing Isaiah's language of scattered Israel gathered. The pilgrim of Psalm 120 who is far away in Meshech is the figure the gospel addresses; the city of God to which the Songs of Ascents ascend is the New Jerusalem of Revelation 21:2-4, where there will be no more war, no more deceitful tongue, and shalom without end."
