    "intro": "Interpretation asks what the text means — moving from observation (what does it say?) to discerning the author's intent in his original context. Psalm 120 is a compressed masterpiece: seven verses that establish the starting condition of the pilgrim's ascent, ground the cry for help in covenant history, indict the deceitful tongue with a divine curse-oracle, and leave the reader in the unresolved ache of prolonged exile. The four movements below trace the psalm's argument from its retrospective confidence to its irresolved close, with attention to genre, canonical placement, and ancient Near Eastern social context.",
