        "title": "Distress answered — past deliverance as the ground of present prayer",
        "range": "120:1",
        "excerpt": "In my trouble I cried to the LORD, and He answered me.",
        "body": "Verse 1 is formally retrospective — a perfect-tense report of completed divine action — but functionally it is the opening argument of a petition psalm. The psalmist does not begin with his current need; he begins with God's established character as One who answers. This is the quintessential Psalter logic: cite what God has done as the foundation for asking what God will do. Psalm 22:4-5 does the same ('Our fathers cried to You and were delivered'); Psalm 77:5-12 spends eight verses mining past divine acts before returning to present distress. The pattern is not manipulation; it is covenant reasoning. God has bound Himself to His people by promise, and His past faithfulness is evidence that His promise holds.\n\nThe word translated 'distress' or 'trouble' (*batstsarah*) carries the physical image of a narrow place, a constriction — related to the root *tsar* ('straits,' 'adversary'). The psalmist is not vaguely sad; he is hemmed in, cornered. And into that constricted space, the LORD answers (*anah*) — a verb that in Hebrew can mean both 'to answer speech' and 'to respond to need.' God's answer to a cry from a tight place is itself a loosening of the straits.\n\nFor the Songs of Ascents as a collection, verse 1 functions as the pilgrim's credential. He does not come to Jerusalem as a tourist or a religious formalist; he comes as someone who has already been in distress and already been answered. The journey up is taken by someone who knows from experience that the God at the destination has already met him in the lowest valley.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Batstsarah* (distress) — from *tsar*, narrow, tight, adversarial. *Anah* (answered) — to respond, to speak back, to address a need; used of both verbal and active divine response throughout the Psalter. The perfect-tense verbs (*qarati*, I cried; *wayyaaneni*, and He answered) are typically read as perfects of certainty or as completed past acts — either way, the divine answer is established fact, not hope."
