        "body": "Verse 2 names the specific threat: *sheqer* (falsehood) on the lips, *remiyyah* (treachery) on the tongue. This is not abstract spiritual opposition — it is targeted verbal assault. In the ancient Near Eastern social world, false speech was a lethal weapon. It could overturn a legal judgment (Exodus 23:1), destroy a marriage (Deuteronomy 22:13-19), strip a man of his inheritance, or exile him from his community. The psalmist's soul (*nephesh* — his whole living person) is at stake. He therefore cries for *natsal* — deliverance, being snatched away from danger, the rescue of one imperiled.\n\nVerses 3-4 shift from petition to judicial oracle. The rhetorical question — 'What shall be given to you, and what more shall be done to you, you deceitful tongue?' — is the opening of a divine-court sentence. In the ancient world, this form echoes the rib (legal lawsuit) pattern: the offended party brings the offender before God as Judge and asks what the penalty shall be. The answer is immediately given: sharp warrior's arrows and burning broom-tree coals. The arrows (*chets*) are the weapon of the skilled warrior (*gibbor*), precise and penetrating. The broom-tree (*retem*) coals are proverbially long-burning — ancient travelers valued *retem* charcoal precisely because it retained intense heat for hours after banking, far longer than other wood coals.\n\nThe punishment is proportionate to the crime by a precise irony. The deceitful tongue has used words as weapons — injuring, penetrating, burning the psalmist's reputation and social standing. The divine judgment against it employs the same categories: arrows that penetrate, coals that burn and do not quickly cool. This is not vindictiveness; it is the lex talionis operating through divine justice. The psalmist does not reach for his own sword; he appeals to the Warrior God whose arrows are sharper and whose coals burn longer.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Natsal* (deliver) — to snatch away from danger, rescue from a superior threat; used of God's exodus-rescue. *Sheqer* (lying) — deliberate, harmful falsehood, the content of false witness. *Remiyyah* (deceitful) — from a root meaning slack, treacherous; the tongue that does not deliver what it appears to promise. *Gibbor* (warrior) — the mighty man, the champion; God's arrows come from a warrior whose skill is unmatched. *Retem* (broom tree) — Retama raetam, known for long-burning coals, referenced in 1 Kings 19:4-5 as the tree under which Elijah collapsed in exhaustion."
