        "body": "The exclamation *oyah* ('woe is me') marks the psalm's most acute emotional register — not the measured petition of verse 2 or the judicial oracle of verses 3-4, but raw grief. And the grief has a specific shape: geography. The psalmist is in the wrong place. Meshech is the far north — associated in Genesis 10:2 with Japheth's distant descendants, in Ezekiel 27:13 with weapons-trading barbarians, and in Ezekiel 38-39 with the great hostile army that will come against Israel in the last days. Kedar is the far east and south — the Ishmaelite tribal confederation of the Arabian desert (Genesis 25:13), known for their black tents (Song of Solomon 1:5), their formidable archers (Isaiah 21:17), and their perpetual readiness for raid and war.\n\nAs noted in the observation step, the pairing cannot be literally simultaneous — a person cannot sojourn in both Meshech (Black Sea region) and Kedar (Arabian desert) at the same time. The pairing is therefore rhetorical: together they name the totality of hostile, uncivilized, shalom-alien territory. It is the ancient equivalent of saying 'I am surrounded at every compass point by enemies of peace.' The implied positive — the place that is the opposite of Meshech and Kedar — is Jerusalem, never named in the psalm but gravitationally present in every line of the Songs of Ascents collection.\n\nVerse 6 adds the dimension of duration: '*too long* has my soul had its dwelling.' *Rav* (much, great, long) marks quantity of time, and the quantity has become unbearable. Derek Kidner observes that the accumulated weight of prolonged immersion in a hostile culture is itself a distinct form of suffering — not the sharp wound of a single attack but the slow erosion of the soul by years of inhabiting what it was never made for. The psalmist's *shakhan* (settling, tabernacling) is being done in the wrong tent.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Gur* (sojourn) — to live as a resident alien with no tribal protection or legal standing. *Shakhan* (dwell) — to settle, tabernacle; the same root as *Shekinah* — the irony is that the psalmist's settling is among Kedar's tents, not Zion's sanctuary. *Sane shalom* (those who hate peace) — *sane* is the strong verb for hatred, not mere indifference."
