        "excerpt": "I am for peace, but when I speak, they are for war.",
        "body": "The psalm's final verse is its most theologically loaded — not because of what it resolves, but because of what it refuses to resolve. The psalmist states his fundamental orientation: *ani shalom* — 'I am peace.' Not merely 'I want peace' or 'I seek peace' — the Hebrew predicates peace directly of the person. His identity is oriented toward wholeness, communal flourishing, harmonious order. And the moment he opens his mouth to express that orientation, the response is *milchamah* — war, armed conflict, the antithesis of everything he is.\n\nThe word 'but' (*ve*, here used adversatively) is the psalm's pivot on which its entire emotional weight rests. The psalmist's word of peace produces the opposite effect. This is not naive misunderstanding — it is structural incompatibility of values. The environment of Meshech and Kedar is not merely different from shalom; it is hostile to it. Speech itself becomes the trigger for escalation. Every attempt at peace-making is met with war-readiness.\n\nThe psalm then simply stops. There is no vow of praise, no expression of trust, no anticipatory thanksgiving, no oracle of divine rescue. The last word — in the Hebrew, *milchamah* — hangs in the air. The editors of the Psalter placed exactly this psalm first in the Songs of Ascents because its irresolution is the engine of the pilgrimage. The soul that cannot make peace in Meshech is the soul that will lift its eyes to the hills (Psalm 121:1), that will rejoice when someone says 'Let us go to the house of the LORD' (Psalm 122:1), and that will finally arrive where 'brothers dwell together in unity' (Psalm 133:1). The ache of Psalm 120:7 is what makes Jerusalem necessary. Allen Ross (A Commentary on the Psalms, Kregel) rightly notes that this is one of the Psalter's most sophisticated editorial moves: the peace that is absent in the opening psalm is the peace that defines the destination.\n\nFor the Christian reader, the New Testament presses this typology forward. Jesus says 'Blessed are the peacemakers' (Matthew 5:9) and identifies His own coming as bringing peace (Ephesians 2:14-17) — but also notes that His peace is not of the world's kind (John 14:27) and that His word, like the psalmist's, will be met with conflict (Matthew 10:34-36). The pilgrim of Psalm 120 who is for peace and receives war is a figure the gospel inhabits fully: the Servant who 'came to His own, and those who were His own did not receive Him' (John 1:11), whose words of peace were answered with a cross. The Songs of Ascents, read Christologically, trace the path from Calvary's Meshech to the resurrection's Zion.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Ani shalom* — 'I am peace'; the predicate-noun construction is strong, identifying shalom with the person's core disposition, not merely a preference. *Milchamah* (war) — armed conflict; its placement as the psalm's final word gives it terminal rhetorical weight. The entire seven-verse arc ends on this word, which is precisely what the journey of the remaining fourteen psalms is designed to overcome."
